    fourteenth anniversary meeting of the SCI at the Crown and Anchor on 2 May 1794 - and was
    afterwards questioned about it by the Privy Council. Wharton may then have given evidence
    against Tooke - according to one account, Wharton relayed the information that Tooke had
    welcomed the prospect of a naval mutiny. 'The Privy Council could not decide whether to call
    Wharton as a prosecution witness or allow Tooke to call him for the defence, when the 
    damnng evidence would be produced under cross-examination. They decided on the latter
    course when Tooke subpoenaed Wharton, but Tooke stymied the prosecution by not calling
    Wharton who was then unable to give evidence against him' (<title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Gentleman Radical</title>, 
    p. 155).</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
    He appears in the diary on 1 November 1794, when Godwin records seeing him at <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HAR02">Hardy's</persName> trial.
    His name is crossed out under 1794 in the 1796 list and mistakenly entered under 1793 - he 
    does not appear in this year. The two instances of 'Warton' in 1789 have been taken as 
    unrelated - different spelling, context unconvincing, pre-date first appearance recorded in 1796
    lists.</p></note><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="printedbook">David and Christina Bewley, <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Gentleman radical: a life of John Horne Tooke, 1736â€“1812</title> 
